Someone executed a (additional) diagnostic action on the system. The action (type, target_component, description, outcome) was: 
TYPE: Test,
TARGET: power supply module internal wiring to output (+) terminal,
DESCRIPTION: With the good battery still installed and 12 V confirmed at the battery, use a continuity tester/ohmmeter (with the battery temporarily removed for resistance checks) to trace the positive path from the battery’s + contact through the PCB/wiring to the PSU output (+) terminal. Verify: (1) continuity from battery + to the point where the PSU LED/resistor branch connects; (2) continuity from that node to the PSU output (+) terminal; and (3) whether the PSU LED/resistor branch is incorrectly tied between the two output terminals instead of across + and −. Look for an open trace, short between the two output terminals, or miswired connection causing the + and − outputs to be shorted together at 12 V.,
RESULT: Continuity from the battery + terminal through the PSU Green LED resistor to the PSU Output Cable (+) is confirmed, and the resistor itself measures nominal at 1 kΩ. The PSU Status LED (green) is between PSU Output Cable (+) and PSU Output Cable (−) with approximately 1 kΩ between LED and +, and 0 Ω between LED and −, indicating the LED/resistor branch is wired across the two output terminals. A 1 Ω short is present between PSU Output Cable (+) and PSU Output Cable (−), and between PSU Green LED Resistor and PSU Output Cable (−).
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-21 01:28:19 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module internal output wiring / output terminals', 'power supply module green LED circuit / associated wiring'] hypothesis_explanation='The latest tests show that with a good 12 V battery installed, the battery terminals are correct, but the PSU output (+) and (−) are effectively shorted together (~1 Ω between them). The green LED/resistor branch is found wired directly across the two PSU outputs, and continuity from battery + through the LED resistor to the PSU Output (+) is correct. A 1 Ω short exists between PSU Output (+) and PSU Output (−) and between the LED resistor node and Output (−). This indicates an internal wiring/PCB fault in the power supply module: either the two output terminals are bridged (solder bridge, damaged trace, or miswire) or the LED circuit/wiring is incorrectly connected so as to short + to −. This short at the power supply module prevents any useful voltage from appearing along the series chain, explains why all module LEDs and the load lamp are off, and is consistent with all measurements so far. Repairing/replacing the PSU output wiring/terminals and correcting the LED circuit connections to remove the short should restore proper 12 V to the rest of the system.'
