description: Visually inspect Control Module 3, focusing on the cable pair that includes the anomalous Control Input Cable (+) 3 whose ‘n’ port was found floating. Open the module access panel and verify how both of its input cables and both of its output cables are actually connected to the internal PCB terminals. Check whether any of the four cables is completely unplugged, plugged onto the wrong terminal, or swapped with another cable pair, and note exactly which external connector corresponds to the internal 12 V and 0 V line terminals., outcome='Control Input Cable (+) 3 still has its ‘n’ port floating, with its ‘p’ port shared with Control Output Cable (+) 2. Control Input Cable (−) 3 is connected on both ports, sharing its ‘p’ with Control Output Cable (−) 2 and its ‘n’ with Control Output Cable (−) 3. Control Output Cables (+) 3 and (−) 3 are each looped on both their own ports, with their ‘n’ ports also connected to Control Input Cables (+) 4 and (−) 4 respectively, and no internal module fault is visually observable.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=65.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
